result.execSummary:
The defendant Alexander H. HEIN was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-Building or Dwelling, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Petition and Stipulation to Waive Appearance and Hearing; Order Extending Probation ordering that defendant's probation be extended for a period of one (1) year or until all court obligations are completed.  New discharge date of 01-20-21.
Duplicate original delivered to DOC.
Petition and Stipulation to Waive Appearance and Hearing.

There is a motion to extend the defendants probation. The defendant did not sign and requested a hearing based on the Departments recommendation. 
The defendant does not wish to have an attorney represent him for todays proceedings. The Court finds that the defendant is freely, knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waiving his right to an attorney and allows him to represent himself. 
The sole issue of this hearing then is to if the defendant has and will exercise due diligence in paying restitution. 
The Court finds that the parties have stipulated to the first issue of contention which is that the restitution has not been paid. 
Testimony presented.
The defendant agrees to the extension and will sign the paperwork. 
The Court accepts the agreement of the parties.
